East German/GDR cuisine was just various salty, bitter, sour, or cold soups with cabbage, fish heads, pickled vegetables, brine, lemon juice, and raw salt. All of them intended as hangover remedies. It was basically a collective attempt to reengineer aspirin in the form of soup.

My buddy the other day was telling me how he put a bunch of aspirin (local brand, ingredients: just acetylsalicylic acid & starch) in the jar of pickles and other vegetables he was pickling, it's a popular folk practice here, so I guess there was also actual aspirin in the soups.

Old man mindset. Going to bed at 20:00 and waking up four in the morning then going for a long walk. One cigar a day, single glass of spirits. Breakfast is toast with fruit preserves and coffee, tea. Supper eaten at five. Afterwards you sit and smoke outside your hose or balcony.

Watching Cormac McCarthy's interview on Oprah and it's striking how conscious he is of the limitations and deceptions of words when speaking. I guess he admired the young nuclear physicist of the previous century because they ended up expressing themselves in an objective way.

Evola's "The Decay of Words" dictionary-essay is a good example of how words change their meaning in crisis, through cycles, civilizations, etc., so one looks back and often finds only what is of today inside old texts. Most would read chivalric romances as a mere sentimentality.

McCarthy focuses on the "subconscious" that he sees as "older than language", because in it he finds a buoy above the tide of time that empties and fills the word-vessels. He's careful when talking, very brief, because he intuits every word he says is a sea of potential meanings.

Gene Wolfe deals with this "subconscious" level of thought-below-words in an interview about the language of Ascians from BoTNS, where he explains even in the context of a language system designed to enslave or limit man's ability to express himself, this layer remains sovereign.
